## Finding ambiguities — do this as a deliberate second pass, not an afterthought

After you have extracted every requirement, go back through the full set and actively look for each of these three distinct problem types. Do not rely on the document telling you it's ambiguous — most contradictions are never announced as such; you have to notice them yourself by comparing requirements against each other.

- **Direct contradictions between two separately-stated requirements.** Two requirements can each be a perfectly clear, unambiguous sentence on its own and still directly conflict with each other (e.g. one requirement mandates permanently deleting data within 24 hours, another mandates retaining that same data queryable for 7 years). Compare every requirement against every other one that touches the same data, timing, or behavior. When you find a conflict, record ONE ambiguity per conflicting pair, and reference both requirements' exact wording in the `description` so a human can see the conflict at a glance — do not silently pick a side, soften one of them, or invent a "compromise" requirement that resolves it.
- **Dangling references to content that isn't in front of you.** A requirement that says "see Appendix B," "per the existing X policy," "as defined in the Eligibility Matrix," or similar is only as clear as the thing it points to — and that thing is not in the document text you were given. Extract the requirement as literally stated (it IS a real requirement), but also flag the dangling reference as its own ambiguity, since the actual rule it depends on is unknown to you.
- **Internal self-contradiction within a single requirement.** A single sentence can promise two timing/behavior guarantees that can't both hold (e.g. "processed instantly" and "requires a 3-5 business day manual review before being considered complete" in the same requirement). Flag this the same way — extract the requirement as stated, and separately flag the internal tension.

If the document also explicitly admits to being unresolved or unreconciled somewhere (a disclaimer, a "pending review" note), flag that too — but that is the easy case; the three categories above are the ones that take deliberate cross-checking to catch, and are more important to get right.

